result.execSummary:
The defendant Logan Wayne Olson-Flood was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of THC (2nd+ Offense) [Modifiers: Repeater], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(e).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

superMiscConds.notes: To be paid out of money seized by the Merrillan Police Department.  The Merrillan Police Department is ordered to turn over the $1,167.00 that was seized during arrest to the Jackson County Clerk of Court's office.
Seek and maintain employment, commensurate with his treatment needs.

Not to possess or consume any controlled substances.   Not to possess any drug paraphernalia.  Not to possess any prescription medications of any kind unless those have been prescribed to the defendant by a physician, and in that case, the defendant shall take such medications only as prescribed.  Defendant shall not alter the form of any prescription prior to, or in conjunction with, ingestion.  Not to associate with any known illegal drug users or dealers.

Defendant to be subject to random testing by his agent.

The defendant shall comply with any treatment, evaluations and/or programming as deemed appropriate by a risk and needs assessment and the agent.  Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with extended supervision conditions.

Court advised defendant of the DNA submission requirement.

ADA Melissa Inlow appeared for the State.  Defendant appeared in person, in custody, with Attorney Poss.   Waive reading of the amended information.  Defendant plead no contest to Count 1 of the amended information.    Court reviewed the charges and possible penalties of the count the defendant plead to.   Defendant understood.  Prior conviction confirmed with the defendant and Attorney Poss.   Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights and elements with the defendant.  He understood. Defense stipulated that there is a factual basis for the plea.   Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily, knowingly and intelligently entered his plea and waived his constitutional rights.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Found guilty of Possession of THC (2nd+ Offense) contrary to 961.41(3g)(e), as a repeater, contrary to 939.62(1)(b).  Joint recommendation for:  4 years total sentence.  Bifurcated as 2 years initial confinement and 2 years extended supervision, concurrent with the sentence he is serving on Winnebago County Case No.  16CF493. Defendant Logan Wayne Flood in court with attorney Matthew Prior.  Gerald Roger Fox appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  State calls witness, M.J., sworn, testifies.  2 registered owners of vehicle and one was suspended.  Stopped vehicle - male operator, ID's defendant - record reflects ID.  Describes his encounter with defendant.  Could smell odor of THC.  Searched vehicle and found evidence in center counsel.  Exhibit 1 - plastic baggie with green material; tested positive for THC; 4 gms.  Exhibit 1 offered/admitted.  Exhibit 2 - Green container  of hashish 87 grams - Exhibit 2 offered/admitted.  Exhibit 3, 4, 5 - Photos of cash in defendant's wallet, found in car, on his person; witness testified to exhibits.  Deposit slip showing $500 taken out from payroll check - less than half of what's in photo.  Exhibits 3, 4, 5 offered/admitted.  Overheard him tell his mother he had more than what was found.  Defense cross - examines witness.  State re-directs questioning of witness.  Re-cross by defense.  State moves for bind over.  No witnesses by defense.  Court binds over for trial.  State files Information.  Defense will schedule arraignment with J. O.  Bond continued.
